{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501320"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:27:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:27:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1746"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1746"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.75,0.14,0,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1746"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109571"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1746"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1746"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91954"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"1453"},{"type":"tags","id":"2771"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3386"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3451"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12914"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32104"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32201"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40369"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40406"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42383"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109571"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department by his wife with confusion for the last 24 hours. While waiting, he has a syncopal episode and ECG monitoring captures the below image. He regains consciousness shortly and his ECG returns to sinus rhythm. He has a medical history of atrial fibrillation and hypercholesterolaemia, and takes apixaban, sotalol and atorvastatin daily.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ventricular tachycardia","Torsades de pointes (TdP)","Ventricular fibrillation","Atrial tachycardia","Atrial flutter"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ECG is consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Etorsades de pointes. \u003C/strong\u003ETorsades is a potentially life threatening arrhythmia caused by QT prolongation, recognised on ECG by tachycardia and cyclical alteration of the QRS axis. This can be congenital or acquired, when acquired it is often caused by anti-arrhythmic drugs such as sotalol, electrolyte disturbances including hypokalaemia, hypomagnesaemia and hypocalcaemia, and structural heart disease. TdP is often short-lived and self-terminating, as described in the clinical scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentricular tachycardia\u003C/strong\u003E is a wide QRS complex tachycardia (Image 1) producing similar appearing QRS complexes as opposed to the winding complexes in TdP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentricular fibrillation\u003C/strong\u003E (Image 2) would not spontaneously revert without intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtrial tachycardia\u003C/strong\u003E has narrow QRS complexes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtrial flutter\u003C/strong\u003E has narrow QRS complexes and classically has a \u0027sawtooth\u0027 pattern (Image 3).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Torsades de pointes is a life threatening arrhythmia with risk of developing ventricular fibrillation.","QT prolongation, often due to medications or electrolyte disturbances, is a key risk factor for torsades de pointes."],"references":["El-Sherif N, Turitto G, Boutjdir M. Acquired long QT syndrome and torsade de pointes. Pacing Clin Electrophysiol. 2018 Apr;41(4):414-421. doi: 10.1111/pace.13296. Epub 2018 Mar 30. PMID: 29405316. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29405316/","Cohagan B, Brandis D. Torsade de Pointes. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459388/","Trinkley KE, Page RL 2nd, Lien H, Yamanouye K, Tisdale JE. QT interval prolongation and the risk of torsades de pointes: essentials for clinicians. Curr Med Res Opin. 2013 Dec;29(12):1719-26. doi: 10.1185/03007995.2013.840568. Epub 2013 Sep 23. PMID: 24020938. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24020938/","Burns E, Buttner R. Polymorphic VT and Torsades de Pointes (TdP). Life in the Fast Lane ECG Library; 2025 Jul 15 [cited 2025 Jul 22]. Available from: https://litfl.com/polymorphic-vt-and-torsades-de-pointes-tdp/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91954"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1746"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21941"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"1844"},{"type":"media","id":"1845"},{"type":"media","id":"21799"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21941"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2jgqWrnZVgwYxdlHTJDMQE2gnBIRhA.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2jgqWrnZVgwYxdlHTJDMQE2gnBIRhA.jpg","isProcessed":true,"widt